<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-07-21T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-07-21T19:00:00-05:00" n="690" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d690">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">867N.01/800: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-07-21T20:00:00-04:00">July 21, 1937—8
                                    p.m.</date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>120. Your 244, July 20, noon.<note n="22" xml:id="d690fn22">Not
                                    printed.</note> In as much as the Palestine question is
                                presumably one for consideration at this stage only by the Mandates
                                Commission and the Council, the Department would be interested in
                                learning in what manner it is likely to come before the
                                Assembly.</p>
                            <p>Is the Department correct in assuming that the protests received by
                                the Secretary General are accorded no official recognition since
                                they are not submitted within the League rules regarding petitions
                                concerning mandated territories?</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>